Rating: 4
Okay, I tackled this dish for the second time, for a crowd of 8. I cooked it in my huge Mauviel roasting pan, so I could go from stovetop to oven, with just some foil on top for the roasting portion. I used 8 chicken breasts and 4 chicken leg quarters, a whole head of garlic, about 6 tablespoons of fresh chopped rosemary, 2 cups of white wine, and two cups of chicken broth, and a large can of good Italian crushed tomatoes. My comments are: brown the chicken really well - it adds to the taste and final presentation. Be careful that you don't burn the garlic - I turned the heat down quite low and browned the garlic with the proscuitto and rosemary very gently, before adding the liquids. Cook at a higher temp than the recipe: I cooked at 375 for an hour and a half. The meat stayed juicy and practically fell off the bone. I didn't bother reducing the sauce - just spooned it over the chicken and some orzo. Some roasted asparagus on the side made for a great meal. Really really delicious - my guests didn't leave a smear on their plates, and asked for seconds. This was great for an Italian-flavoured summer feast, and I could cook it a day ahead, and reheat in the oven. Highly recommended recipe.

